Miracle seeds: Biased expectations, complementary input use, and the dynamics
 of smallholder technology adoption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
To fully benefit from new agricultural technologies like improved seed varieties
, significant investment in complementary inputs such as fertilizers and
 pesticides, and practices such as systematic planting, irrigation, and
 weeding are also required.
 Farmers may fail to recognize the importance of these complements, leading
 to disappointing crop yields and outputs and, eventually, dis-adoption
 of the improved variety.
 Using a field experiment, we test an information intervention among smallholder
 maize farmers in eastern Uganda that points out these complimentarities
 and find that this leads to lower adoption in the treatment group.
 We rationalize this finding with a simple model where farmers have misspecified
 mental models of the technology production function.
 Consistent with the theoretical model, we find that most farmers in our
 sample believe in miracle seed, leading them to adopt less after they have
 been sensitized about the need to use complementary inputs to unlock the
 adoption premium.
\end_layout

