\begin_layout Subsection
Impact on adoption
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Impact-on-adoption"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start with the main hypothesis of this paper: whether farmers who were
 pointed out that improved varieties need substantial investment in complementar
y inputs and management practices behave differently in terms of seed use
 in subsequent seasons than farmers that were not similarly informed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we determine if farmers adopted improved maize varieties.
 To do so, we asked farmers on how many plots they cultivated maize during
 the preceding season.
 From these plots, we randomly selected one plot and asked detailed questions
 about seed and varietal use, input use, and management practices.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The decision to ask detailed questions on only one (randomly selected) plot
 as opposed to asking details on all plots was made because there is generally
 high correlation between technology use, input use and management practices
 within a household.
 As such, we decided to increase the number of farmers at the expense of
 the number of plots as this would increase statistical power.
 That said, one may be worried that farmers use different seed on different
 plots, and if the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

wrong
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 plot is chosen, a farmer that is actually an adopting farmer is categorized
 as a non-adopter.
 We investigated this issue further by using a different variable for adoption
 status, namely if the farmer used seed of an improved variety on any field,
 and results were very similar.
 Furthermore, selection of the plot happens only during baseline; at other
 surveys reference is made to the name of the plot that was randomly selected
 during baseline.
 Provided that farmers plant the same seed type on the same plot every season,
 this would also mean that adoption dynamics are not affected by the random
 selection process.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Based on the information collected, we then defined a farmer as an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Adopter
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 if they used either non-recycled (newly purchased, not saved) seed of (a)
 a hybrid or (b) an open pollinated variety.
 All others were defined as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Non-adopters.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We acknowledge that this definition of adoption is not perfect.
 Seed of an open pollinated variety that has been recycled (saved) up to
 four times could still be considered as improved, and farmers using this
 seed could still be counted as adopters.
 However, we expect the problem of incorrect beliefs about 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

miracle seeds
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and biased expectations to be most pronounced when smallholders do not
 have experience with the seed.
 If farmers recycle and use seed several times, their beliefs about the
 relationship between efforts and the returns to improved varieties will
 become closer to reality as they learn from season to season.
 That is why this stricter definition is useful to answer the questions
 raised in this paper.
 Also, most of our results remain robust to different definitions of adoption.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 A second related outcome we consider is the use of recycled seed, which
 is defined as seed that a farmer has saved themselves or obtained from
 another farmer who saved it (for example, a neighbor or relative).
 Another third related outcome is the share of farmers that report having
 purchased seed from an agro-input shop.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Results are summarized in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Treatment-effects"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Column (1) shows sample means of the four outcomes at baseline with standard
 deviations in the brackets below.
 We find that 44 percent of farmers use fresh seed of improved varieties
 and that one third of farmers reports that the seed that they planted on
 the randomly selected plot was obtained from an agro-input dealer.
 Column (2) shows the difference between treatment and control groups for
 outcomes after the intervention.
 Our theory suggests that in response to being sensitized about the importance
 of using complementary inputs and management practices when using an improved
 variety, some farmers (Types 3 and 6) will change their adoption behavior
 (Prediction 2 in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Theoretical-framework"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 A relatively large share of farmers that initially overestimated the probabilit
y of an adoption premium (Type 3) will dis-adopt as their expected marginal
 return is reduced by the treatment.
 A share of farmers that initially underestimated the returns to improved
 varieties (Type 6) may start adopting as their expected marginal return
 is increased by the treatment.
 We find that adoption, as measured by the index, significantly decreases
 for the entire sample.
 Furthermore, all coefficients move in the direction of dis-adoption.
 This implies that farmers are less likely to use improved seed and seed
 bought at an agro-input shop but more likely to use farmer-saved seed in
 accordance with our earlier definitions of adoption.
 Since the two opposing effects for farmer Types 3 and 6 partly cancel each
 other out, the dis-adoption effect is not pronounced in the entire sample.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To separate the two opposing effects, we restrict the sample to farmers
 that do not use complementary inputs at baseline in Column (3).
 We see that the estimated effects become stronger when we restrict attention
 to this subgroup.
 Farmers who were exposed to the treatment are almost eight percentage points
 less likely to adopt fresh seed of an improved variety.
 We see another particularly strong increase in the share of farmers that
 uses seed recycled from the previous harvest in the treatment group and
 a somewhat lower but still significant reduction in farmers who bought
 seed from an agro-input dealer.
 The treatment also has a significant and more pronounced negative effect
 on the adoption index for this subgroup of farmers that adopted at baseline.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Going one step further, in column (4) we restrict attention to the sample
 of farmers that do not use complementary inputs at baseline and also overestima
te the adoption premium (Type 3 farmers).
 According to Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "types of farmers"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we expect that especially these farmer types would accelerate disadoption
